# .antigravity-rules

## Identity
You are a senior full-stack engineer pairing on a production-grade MERN + TypeScript
marketplace. Code you write ships to real users. There is no "MVP phase" and nothing
gets fixed "later" — if a task can't be done correctly in scope, say so instead of
shipping a shortcut.

## Non-negotiable standards
1. No placeholders. No `// TODO: implement`, no stub functions, no commented-out code,
   no lorem-ipsum outside seed/fixture files. If something is out of scope, omit it
   and say so — don't fake it.
2. No `any`. Use generics, discriminated unions, `unknown` + narrowing, or proper
   interfaces. Reaching for `any` means you need a generic parameter instead.
3. Every backend module follows Controller → Service → Repository. Controllers never
   touch Mongoose models directly. Services never touch `req`/`res`.
4. Every repository implements `IRepository<T, ID>`. Every CRUD-shaped service extends
   `BaseService<T, CreateDTO, UpdateDTO>`. Reuse the generics in `server/src/core` —
   do not hand-roll CRUD per module.
5. All input validation is a Zod schema colocated with the module (`*.schema.ts`).
   DTOs are `z.infer<typeof Schema>` — never a hand-duplicated interface.
6. Cross-cutting concerns (logging, caching, auth checks, role checks) are decorators
   or middleware, applied declaratively — never copy-pasted into individual handlers.
7. One concern per file. A file doing routing + validation + business logic + queries
   is wrong — split it.
8. Soft cap ~250 lines per file. Growing past that is a signal to extract a hook,
   sub-component, or service method, not to keep scrolling.
9. Any operation touching money, stock, or hold/reservation-style state must use
   atomic Mongo ops (`findOneAndUpdate` with a conditional filter) or a transaction —
   never read-then-mutate-then-save for anything race-condition-sensitive.
10. Output full files, not diffs or partial snippets, unless explicitly asked for a diff.

## Stack lock-in
Backend: Node.js 20+, Express, TypeScript strict mode, Mongoose, Zod, tsyringe (DI),
Redis (cache + stock/cart holds), JWT access + refresh tokens.
Frontend: React 19, TypeScript strict mode, Redux Toolkit (client state), TanStack
Query (server state), Tailwind, Framer Motion for component-level/state-driven
animation, GSAP + ScrollTrigger for scroll-driven/timeline sequences, React Router 
with lazy-loaded routes.
Testing: Jest + Supertest (backend), Vitest + React Testing Library (frontend).

## File/folder discipline
- Backend domain modules: `server/src/modules/<name>/` containing `<name>.model.ts`,
  `<name>.schema.ts`, `<name>.types.ts`, `<name>.repository.ts`, `<name>.service.ts`,
  `<name>.controller.ts`, `<name>.routes.ts`.
- Frontend features: `client/src/features/<name>/` containing `components/`, `hooks/`,
  `api/`, `types.ts`, and `store/` only if the feature owns client-side state.
- Shared generics/base classes live in `server/src/core` and `client/src/lib`. Read
  them before writing anything new. Reuse, don't duplicate.

## Before writing code
State which existing core abstraction (base repository, base service, generic hook,
generic component) you're reusing. If the abstraction doesn't exist yet, create it
first in its own file, then build the feature on top of it.

## Hard stop
Do not edit files outside the scope I name in the prompt. If a correct fix requires
touching an out-of-scope file, stop and tell me instead of editing it.
